"# Codex Implementation Brief\n\n## Objective\nImplement the MVP of an AI-powered movie production platform (web + tablet responsive) that centralizes pre-production workflows for film studios. Build a production-ready, secure, testable, and deployable codebase consistent with the Final Project Specification. Deliver the platform to meet the Acceptance Criteria and operational targets specified.\n\nDo not add features beyond the spec. Build what is described, and produce the missing canonical artifacts (Role & Permission Matrix, OpenAPI v3 spec, ERD and SQL migrations, RLS policies, IaC modules) as part of implementation deliverables.\n\n---\n\n## Required Features\nImplement the following MVP features exactly as specified:\n\n- Multi-organization (tenant) support with shared-DB default and optional per-org DB/bucket provisioning.\n- Project lifecycle (create/view projects, timezone-aware).\n- Script upload, parsing, scene extraction, parsed JSON storage, AI summaries (short & long).\n- People management (CRUD, import, availability windows).\n- Schedules / shoot days with optimistic concurrency + advisory lock endpoints, schedule optimization as async job, conflict detection.\n- Budgeting & cost tracking with deterministic estimator and optional AI-assisted estimates (opt-in).\n- Locations management and map integration hooks.\n- Asset upload via signed URLs, asset_versions, thumbnail generation, previews, version retrieval.\n- Comments, approvals, notifications, audit logs (immutable), and basic dashboards.\n- AI Gateway to centralize all outbound LLM calls, enforce quotas, provide provenance, caching, and synchronous/asynchronous endpoints.\n- Background workers for heavy/CPU-bound tasks (parsing, OCR, thumbnails, optimization).\n- Observability (OpenTelemetry traces, Sentry errors, metrics), secrets management (managed secret store + KMS), backup & erase workflows, and CI/CD pipeline with contract tests.\n\nDeliverables (explicit, required):\n- Role & Permission Matrix (canonical).\n- Full OpenAPI v3 spec covering /api/v1/ endpoints and schemas.\n- ERD and SQL migration scripts (with concrete column types, FKs, indexes).\n- RLS policy SQL scripts integrated into migrations for shared-DB mode.\n- Terraform IaC modules for infra provisioning (shared and per-tenant DB/bucket).\n- Test dataset for AI evaluation and E2E flows.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture\nFollow the Final Architecture Decisions precisely. Implement the topology below and make each decision explicit in code and documentation.\n\n1. Tenancy\n   - Default: Single Postgres DB with strict org-scoped rows + DB Row-Level Security (RLS).\n   - Optional per-org: automated provisioning of separate DB instances and storage buckets via Org Provisioner Terraform modules.\n   - Enforce org_id equality in DB policies and API middleware. Never trust client-supplied org_id.\n\n2. Services\n   - Frontend: React + TypeScript deployed to Vercel (preview per PR).\n   - API: Node.js + TypeScript REST API. Fastify recommended. Deploy production-critical endpoints as long-lived managed Node services; non-critical can be serverless only if connection pooling (PgBouncer) is used.\n   - Workers: Node.js worker processes (BullMQ + Redis) or cloud tasks. Workers run in containers with resource limits and must be idempotent.\n   - AI Gateway: Node.js (or Python) service that proxies all LLM calls, imposes quotas, logs cost, enforces prompt templates, PII redaction, and caching. Provide synchronous and asynchronous endpoints.\n   - DB: Postgres (Supabase for MVP or managed Postgres).\n   - Storage: S3-compatible (signed URLs). CDN-backed serving (CloudFront/Cloudflare).\n   - Cache & Queue: Redis for caching, locks, and BullMQ (or managed queue alternatives).\n   - Optional optimization microservice: Python + OR-Tools exposed via REST/gRPC.\n\n3. Communication & Concurrency\n   - Realtime: Start with Supabase Realtime + presence; allow pluggable replacement (Ably/Pusher) if scaling needed.\n   - Concurrency: Optimistic concurrency with version_token/ETag on entities. API enforces version_token on mutating requests. Provide lock/lease endpoints for critical drag/drop operations.\n\n4. Observability & Operations\n   - OpenTelemetry across frontend, API, workers, AI Gateway.\n   - Sentry for errors; Prometheus/Grafana or hosted for metrics and alerting.\n   - Structured JSON logs with redaction and audit logs in append-only storage.\n   - Backups: daily logical backups for shared DB; DB-level backups for per-tenant DBs. Tag backups with metadata.\n\n---\n\n## Technology Requirements\nStrictly follow these tech choices and constraints:\n\n- Frontend: React + TypeScript, Chakra UI or Tailwind (WCAG AA). Use React Query (TanStack) for server state. E2E: Cypress.\n- Backend: Node.js + TypeScript. Fastify recommended. Use OpenAPI-generated TypeScript client stubs where possible.\n- Workers: Node.js + TypeScript with BullMQ/Redis. Ensure idempotency, DLQ, and traceability.\n- DB: Postgres (Supabase or managed).\n- Storage: S3-compatible + CDN. Use signed URLs for direct-to-storage uploads.\n- AI Gateway: centralized proxy for LLM providers with per-org quotas, token accounting, prompt templates, PII redaction, caching by input hash + prompt_template_id + model_version.\n- IaC: Terraform modules for infra including per-tenant provisioning and PgBouncer.\n- CI: GitHub Actions. Restrict secret exposure in PRs.\n- Security tools: Snyk or equivalent SCA; SBOM generation and pinned deps where practical.\n- Observability: OpenTelemetry + Sentry; metrics in Prometheus/Grafana or hosted.\n\nTechnical constraints and quotas:\n- Script file size: <= 20 MB for synchronous parse (MVP). If >20MB accept via async flow with progress reporting.\n- Other assets: up to 200 MB via resumable uploads (S3 multipart / tus). Larger media deferred to external storage.\n- Access token lifetime: <= 15 minutes. Refresh tokens rotate on use; expire after configurable window (default suggested 30 days).\n- AI Gateway: synchronous for short tasks (<15s typical), asynchronous for heavy tasks.\n- Realtime propagation: <2s in-session goal.\n- API median latency target under nominal load: <300ms (AI endpoints handled separately).\n\n---\n\n## Folder Structure\nImplement a monorepo layout. Use TypeScript workspaces (pnpm/yarn/npm). Example structure (explicit tasks to create):\n\n- /apps\n  - /web-frontend/ (React + TypeScript, Vercel)\n  - /api/ (Fastify Node.js TypeScript REST API)\n  - /ai-gateway/ (Node.js TypeScript service)\n  - /workers/ (BullMQ workers)\n  - /optimize-service/ (optional Python OR-Tools service)\n- /packages\n  - /ts-sdk/ (TypeScript SDK generated from OpenAPI)\n  - /ui/ (shared UI components)\n  - /db/ (migration helpers, seed scripts)\n  - /shared-types/ (common TypeScript types)\n- /infra\n  - /terraform/modules/ (org-provisioner, db, storage, redis)\n  - /k8s/ (optional)\n- /migrations/ (SQL migration scripts & RLS policy scripts)\n- /tests/\n  - /e2e/ (Cypress)\n  - /integration/\n  - /ai-tests/ (LLM regression dataset)\n- /docs/ (ERD, Role & Permission Matrix, prompt templates, runbooks)\n- /scripts/ (dev seed, local infra helpers)\n\nMake this structure explicit in repo init scripts and README.\n\n---\n\n## Database Requirements\nImplement the database following the spec. Required actions:\n\n1. Deliver a complete ERD and SQL migration files with concrete column types, constraints, and indexes for all primary tables listed in the spec. Include FK relationships, NOT NULL where required, and sensible varchar/text limits.\n   - Examples of required columns (implement exact types in migration files):\n     - organizations (id UUID PK, name text, region text, plan text, settings jsonb, created_at timestamptz)\n     - users (id UUID PK, org_id UUID FK, email text unique, name text, roles jsonb or normalized role table, last_active timestamptz, mfa_enabled boolean, status enum)\n     - projects (id UUID, org_id, title text, timezone text, start_date date, end_date date, status enum, version_token text, created_by UUID, created_at timestamptz)\n     - scripts, script_parses, scenes, people, locations, schedules/shoot_days, schedule_assignments, budgets, assets, asset_versions, comments, approvals, audit_logs, notifications, ai_requests, jobs\n   - Provide tsvector columns for script text and comments; create GIN indexes on them.\n   - Separate parsed JSON (script_parses) to avoid row bloat.\n   - Provide soft-delete columns (deleted boolean, deleted_at timestamptz) where specified.\n\n2. RLS Policies\n   - Create and include in migrations explicit RLS policies that enforce org_id equality for shared DB.\n   - Policies must derive org_id from JWT claims (supabase.auth.claims or validated JWT), not from request body.\n   - Apply stricter RLS policies for sensitive tables: budget_items, approvals, audit_logs.\n   - Provide migration scripts that enable RLS for applicable tables and include SQL examples for common permission checks (read for org members, write for roles).\n\n3. Indexing & Materialized Views\n   - Indexes: (org_id, project_id, created_at), primary keys on id, scenes: (script_id, scene_number), and other indexes as per usage.\n   - Materialized views for dashboard aggregates and scheduled refresh intervals.\n\n4. Versioning & Retention\n   - Implement asset_versions and script_parses tables. Retain last N versions by default; make configurable per org.\n   - Implement archival/purge jobs and store immutable audit logs separately.\n\n5. DB Connection Pooling\n   - Design for PgBouncer/proxy in infra and migration docs. Document pooling configuration in infra.\n\n6. Deliverables (explicit):\n   - ERD (diagram + SQL).\n   - SQL migration files that create tables, indexes, constraints, and RLS policies.\n   - Automated RLS unit/integration tests executed in CI.\n\nNote: do not store large blobs in DB; store references to storage.\n\n---\n\n## API Requirements\nImplement RESTful JSON API versioned at /api/v1/ with these requirements and explicit contracts to implement:\n\nGeneral\n- Base path: /api/v1/\n- Authentication: short-lived access JWTs. Derive effective org_id from JWT; ignore client-supplied org_id.\n- Correlation header: accept X-Correlation-ID; generate new correlation ID if missing and propagate in logs/traces.\n- Error envelope: { code: string, message: string, details?: any }\n- Pagination: cursor-based (?page_size=50&cursor=<opaque_cursor>).\n- Rate-limit headers: X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset.\n- CORS and TLS enforced.\n- API docs via OpenAPI. Generate TypeScript client SDK from OpenAPI.\n\nAuthentication & Session endpoints (implement exactly)\n- POST /auth/signup\n- POST /auth/login → returns { access_token, refresh_token }\n  - access_token TTL <= 15 minutes\n  - refresh_token: one-time-use rotation; set expiry window (configurable; default 30 days)\n- POST /auth/refresh → accepts one-time refresh token; returns new access_token + new refresh_token; revoke old refresh_token\n- POST /auth/logout → revoke session server-side\n- Admin: POST /admin/users/:id/revoke-sessions → immediate session revocation (must propagate to session store and invalidate tokens)\n\nKey resource endpoints (implement as described)\n- Organizations\n  - GET /orgs/:orgId\n  - PATCH /orgs/:orgId/settings\n- Projects\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects\n  - GET /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId\n  - PATCH /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId\n- Scripts\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/scripts\n    - Return signed upload URL. Client uploads file directly to storage, then POST to trigger parse job.\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/scripts/:scriptId/parse → enqueues parse job.\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/scripts/:scriptId/ai-summarize → synchronous if small; include provenance metadata.\n  - GET script, GET versions\n- People\n  - CRUD /orgs/:orgId/people\n  - Bulk import endpoint\n- Schedules\n  - CRUD /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/schedules\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/schedules/optimize → returns 202 + { jobId } for async solver\n  - GET /schedules/:id/conflicts\n  - Lock endpoints: POST /locks (acquireLock), DELETE /locks/:lockId (release)\n- Budgets\n  - CRUD budgets & items\n  - POST /budgets/estimate → async job for heavy estimation\n- Assets\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/assets → returns signed upload URL; client uploads and then triggers processing job\n  - GET preview, GET versions\n- Comments & Approvals\n  - POST /comments\n  - GET /entities/:id/comments\n  - POST /approvals\n  - PATCH /approvals/:id\n- Notifications\n  - GET /users/:userId/notifications\n  - POST /notifications/mark-read\n- AI\n  - Unified AI path: /api/v1/ai/*\n    - POST /api/v1/ai/summarize-script (sync for small)\n    - POST /api/v1/ai/optimize-schedule (async)\n    - Every AI response must include model_used, prompt_template_id, prompt_hash (redacted), generated_at, token_usage, cached boolean.\n- Jobs\n  - GET /jobs/:jobId\n\nConcurrency and optimistic locking\n- Mutating endpoints must require version_token (or send If-Match ETag). On mismatch return 409 with current representation.\n- Implement advisory lock endpoints for per-item leases: acquireLock(entityId, ttl) returns lockId and locked_until.\n\nAsync job lifecycle\n- Enqueue jobs with idempotency_key and provenance metadata (who enqueued, correlation_id).\n- Jobs must be retriable with exponential backoff; persistent failures move to DLQ.\n- Provide GET /jobs/:jobId to fetch status and results.\n\nRealtime API\n- Token-based ephemeral auth for realtime channels; channels for schedules, comments, notifications, presence.\n- Notify presence and deltas with <2s in-session propagation target.\n\nOpenAPI & SDK\n- Deliver full OpenAPI v3 spec. CI must validate server against OpenAPI contract tests and generate TypeScript SDK client. Include example request/response payloads in spec.\n\n---\n\n## Security Rules\nImplement the Security Requirements exactly. Make the rules explicit in code, infra, and documentation.\n\nAuthentication & Sessions\n- Use an identity provider (Supabase Auth or equivalent) but enforce server-side session controls.\n- Access token TTL <= 15 minutes.\n- Refresh token: rotate on use; single-use; expiry window configurable (default 30 days).\n- Session revocation must be immediate via server-side session store (Redis). Admin revoke must invalidate sessions within 30s.\n- Implement TOTP MFA for Admin/Finance roles.\n\nAuthorization & RLS\n- Central authorization middleware enforces role-based permissions according to the Role & Permission Matrix (deliverable).\n- Always derive org_id and user identity from validated JWT claims. Ignore client-sent org_id for auth decisions.\n- Implement DB-level RLS policies for shared DB; include tests to ensure no cross-org access.\n\nUploads & Processing\n- Signed direct-to-storage uploads only.\n- Validate file type by magic bytes and MIME. Enforce size quotas.\n- Malware scan incoming files at ingest (cloud provider scanning or ClamAV in worker).\n- Parse/thumbnailing run in isolated worker containers with resource caps.\n- For previews, sanitize content. Do not serve original file raw unless user authorized.\n\nAI / LLM Controls\n- All LLM calls funnel through AI Gateway.\n- Default PII behavior: detect & redact PII before sending to external LLMs unless org explicitly opts-in with documented consent and contract.\n- System prompts and prompt templates are server-side only; sanitize user-supplied content before merging into prompts.\n- Log AI calls (prompt_template_id, model_id, redacted prompt snippet, token_usage, response hash) in ai_requests table. Make logs auditable.\n- Enforce per-org compute budgets and per-request token limits. Provide fail-safe backpressure if exceeded.\n\nSecrets & Keys\n- Use managed secret store (AWS Secrets Manager/GCP Secret Manager/Vault).\n- Store OAuth refresh tokens in DB encrypted with envelope encryption via KMS.\n- Rotate credentials and provide admin revoke endpoints.\n\nTransport & Network\n- TLS everywhere; least-privilege IAM roles for cloud resources.\n- Do not expose secrets in logs or in CI.\n\nAudit & Tamper Resistance\n- Audit logs append-only with immutable hash column stored separately.\n- Retention and WORM policies configurable per org.\n\nCI/CD & Supply Chain\n- Restrict secrets in CI; disallow PR fork access to secrets.\n- Pin critical dependencies when practical; run SCA (Snyk) and SBOM generation.\n\nIncident & Pen Testing\n- Provide incident runbook; monthly backup restore tests; pen testing before public release.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Requirements\nImplement the complete testing strategy and automation defined in the spec.\n\nTest suites & tooling\n- Unit tests: Jest. Cover business logic (parsers, estimators, auth middleware). High coverage on critical modules (parsing, cost calc, authorization).\n- Integration tests: DB migrations, RLS policies, API endpoints. Use ephemeral test DBs seeded with sample datasets.\n- E2E tests: Cypress for core flows (project creation, script upload & parse, schedule create & optimize, approval flow).\n- Contract tests: OpenAPI-based validations between server and client SDK.\n- AI evaluation: regression tests for LLM outputs on synthetic dataset (expected summaries, hallucination tracking). Store expected outputs and thresholds.\n- Security tests: SCA, DAST, static analysis, RLS & RBAC positive/negative tests.\n- Performance & Load: k6 or Artillery profiles for API; stress tests for workers and AI Gateway.\n- Fault injection/chaos: simulate LLM/email/maps outages and verify graceful degradation.\n\nCI Pipeline (explicit steps)\n- Pre-merge (PR): lint, typecheck, unit tests.\n- Merge: integration tests, contract tests, E2E smoke (fast subset).\n- Post-merge: deploy to staging, run smoke tests, run backup restore automation test.\n- Manual: promote to production after curated smoke tests and SLO checks.\n\nTest data & staging\n- Seed staging with synthetic dataset for reproducible AI and QA tests. Include DST/timezone test cases for scheduling.\n\nCoverage & Acceptance\n- Enforce CI gating on test suites. Define and enforce coverage thresholds for critical modules (set these values in CI config; not required to invent numbers in this doc—establish them with product/QA).\n- RLS policy tests must be part of CI to prevent regressions.\n\nOperational tests\n- Monthly automated DB & storage restore test in staging.\n\nDeliverables (tests and artifacts)\n- AI test dataset + expected outputs.\n- RLS unit tests and integration tests.\n- OpenAPI contract tests.\n- E2E test scripts for acceptance criteria.\n\n---\n\n## Definition of Done\nFor each Acceptance Criterion from the Final Specification, deliver code + automated tests + docs demonstrating behavior. The following checklist is required before merging release to production:\n\nFunctional acceptance (automated where possible)\n1. Project creation: automated test that creates & lists project; appears in dashboard.\n2. Script upload & summarization:\n   - Signed URL upload flow implemented.\n   - Parse job completes within SLO (typical < 2 minutes) for typical files; tests assert parsed scenes stored.\n   - AI short summary (2–3 sentences) and long summary (paragraph) produced within 15s for typical prompts or returned via async job. Summaries include provenance metadata recorded in ai_requests table.\n3. People management: create/import 10 people in tests, assign to scenes, edit availability.\n4. Schedules & optimization:\n   - Create 5-day schedule in tests; optimization job returns viable alternative that reduces location moves >10% on provided test dataset (heuristic test).\n   - Conflict detection tests identify overlapping person assignments.\n5. Budgeting & cost estimation: deterministic estimator unit tests and sample outputs; AI-assisted estimate available as opt-in, logged.\n6. Assets & versioning: upload via signed URL, create version, retrieve older versions, and preview thumbnails via API tests.\n7. Collaboration & approvals: posting comment delivers in-app notification and queues email; approval action writes an audit log entry (assertion in tests).\n8. Multi-tenant isolation & auth:\n   - RLS + API tests prove no cross-org access.\n   - Session revocation occurs within 30s in integration test.\n9. Non-functional & operational:\n   - SLOs: provide monitoring dashboards; alerting configured.\n   - Backups: documented RPO <= 24h and RTO for critical services < 4 hours; pass monthly restore test in staging.\n   - Observability: traces, Sentry, metrics configured. Critical alerts in place.\n   - Timezone handling: store timestamps in UTC and tests asserting timezone-aware UI behavior and DST transitions.\n\nOperational & deploy readiness\n- Terraform IaC modules for shared and per-tenant provisioning implemented and tested in automated infra tests.\n- Secrets management integrations (Secrets Manager + KMS) in place.\n- OpenAPI spec present and contract tests passing.\n- SDK generated (TypeScript) and smoke-tested against API.\n- Runbooks: backup/restore, incident response, tenant isolation, and AI cost runaway mitigation documented.\n- Pen test findings remediated (or plan and timeline documented before public release).\n- RLS policy CI gating and automated RLS tests pass.\n\nDocumentation & artefacts\n- Role & Permission Matrix published in /docs.\n- ERD and migration SQL in /migrations and /docs.\n- Prompt templates and AI governance doc stored in /docs.\n- Monitoring dashboards and alert rules documented.\n- Developer onboarding README: local dev seed, how to run infra locally, and how to seed staging.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks (explicit step-by-step)\nBreak the work into explicit implementation tasks for Codex:\n\n1. Repository & scaffolding\n   - Initialize monorepo and folder structure.\n   - Add TypeScript configurations and workspace tooling.\n   - Add ESLint, Prettier, Husky pre-commit hooks. Add commit message guidelines.\n\n2. Database\n   - Produce ERD and SQL migrations for all tables in spec with concrete types.\n   - Implement RLS policies in migrations for shared-DB mode. Add tests.\n   - Add seed data scripts for staging & test fixtures.\n   - Add migrations for audit_logs immutable hashing column.\n\n3. API & Middleware\n   - Implement Fastify-based API with OpenAPI-generated route stubs.\n   - Implement auth middleware that validates JWT, extracts org_id, user_id, role claims.\n   - Implement authorization middleware referencing Role & Permission Matrix (create placeholder matrix doc; API enforces rules from it).\n   - Implement X-Correlation-ID propagation, OpenTelemetry instrumentation, and Sentry integration.\n   - Implement error envelope and rate-limit headers.\n\n4. Auth & Sessions\n   - Implement login/refresh/logout with rotating refresh tokens stored encrypted.\n   - Implement server-side session store in Redis for revocation; admin revoke sessions endpoint.\n\n5. Uploads & Workers\n   - Implement signed upload URL endpoints for scripts and assets.\n   - Implement worker queue (BullMQ + Redis) for parsing, thumbnails, OCR, optimization.\n   - Implement job idempotency keys, DLQ handling, and visibility retries.\n\n6. AI Gateway\n   - Implement AI Gateway service that:\n     - Receives AI requests from API.\n     - Applies prompt templates and sanitization.\n     - Performs PII detection & redaction by default.\n     - Enforces per-org quotas, logs token usage to ai_requests table.\n     - Implements caching keyed by input hash + prompt_template_id + model_version.\n     - Emits provenance metadata in responses.\n   - Expose sync and async endpoints.\n\n7. Realtime & Locks\n   - Implement realtime channels with token-based auth and presence support (begin with Supabase Realtime).\n   - Implement lock endpoints with advisory lock semantics stored in Redis.\n\n8. Assets processing\n   - Worker flows: malware scan, thumbnail generation, PDF parsing, OCR. Store outputs in CDN-enabled bucket.\n   - Enforce file limits: scripts <= 20MB sync; others <=200MB resumable.\n\n9. Testing & CI\n   - Add Jest unit tests, integration test harness, and Cypress E2E tests.\n   - Add OpenAPI contract tests. Add SI tests for RLS.\n   - Configure GitHub Actions per CI pipeline steps.\n\n10. Infra & IaC\n    - Implement Terraform modules for shared infrastructure and per-tenant DB provisioning.\n    - Add PgBouncer config for DB connection pooling.\n    - Provide deploy scripts and staging infra.\n\n11. Documentation\n    - Publish Role & Permission Matrix, ERD, OpenAPI, prompt templates, runbooks, and developer onboarding README.\n\n---\n\n## Coding Standards and Conventions\nFollow and enforce these standards:\n\n- Language: TypeScript everywhere on Node services and frontend.\n- Style: ESLint (Airbnb or recommended baseline) + Prettier. Fail CI on lint errors.\n- Types: Strict TypeScript compiler options (strict: true). Avoid any except where explicitly justified with TODOs and code comments.\n- API contracts: Use OpenAPI-first for endpoints. Generate types/clients from OpenAPI.\n- Logging: Structured JSON logs with fields { timestamp, level, message, correlation_id, org_id?, user_id?, service, trace_id }. Redact PII or secret-like fields prior to logging.\n- Errors: Use centralized error types with stable codes; respond with { code, message, details? }.\n- Security: No secrets in code. Integrate with Secrets Manager and KMS. Do not check secrets into repo.\n- Idempotency: All worker jobs must accept idempotency_key and be safe to re-run.\n- Tests: Unit tests for business logic; integration tests for DB and RLS; E2E for flows. Tests must be deterministic and seedable.\n- Dependencies: Pin critical dependencies; run SCA scans in CI.\n\n---\n\n## Deployment Requirements\nExplicit operational deployment requirements:\n\n- Environments: dev, staging, production. Staging seeded with synthetic dataset for AI and QA.\n- CI/CD: GitHub Actions with preview deployments for PRs; merges trigger staging deploy; manual promotion to production.\n- Secrets: Use managed Secrets Manager, integrate with CI securely.\n- Backup & Restore: Daily logical backups (shared DB), DB instance-level backups for per-tenant DBs. Tag backups with metadata (timestamp, region, tenant_id).\n- RTO/RPO: Documented targets: RPO <= 24 hours; RTO for critical services < 4 hours. Add automated restore tests to validate monthly.\n- Monitoring & Alerts: Prometheus/Grafana or hosted monitoring with alerts for queue backlog, error rates, AI cost runaway, SLO breaches. Integrate PagerDuty/Slack.\n- Autoscaling: API nodes and workers autoscale by CPU/queue depth. Configure PgBouncer and max DB connections.\n- Region / Residency: Terraform modules to provision region-specific DB and storage. Default deploy uses shared Postgres; per-tenant provisioning must be automated.\n- Secrets rotation: Implement rotation policies and document admin revoke flow.\n- Incident response: provide runbooks for tenant isolation incidents, backup restore, and AI cost runaway.\n\n---\n\n## Final Notes & Constraints\n- Do not implement fine-grained CRDT/OT collaborative editing for MVP. Use optimistic concurrency + advisory locks as specified.\n- Start with shared DB default; include per-tenant provisioning in IaC and provisioning workflow/test.\n- Ensure AI features are behind org-level opt-in toggles and do not send data to external LLMs unless org consent is recorded and contracts support it.\n- All AI calls must have provenance metadata stored and surfaced to UI.\n- All RLS policies must be covered by automated tests in CI before any merge to main.\n- Do not store large files in DB; use storage references.\n\n---\n\nThis brief is the canonical implementation instruction. For missing canonical artifacts (Role & Permission Matrix, ERD, OpenAPI spec, RLS SQL), create them as the first code deliverables and include them in the repo under /docs and /migrations. Codex must implement exactly to these instructions and produce the listed deliverables and automated tests to validate all acceptance criteria before sign-off."